reviews.review_text: listening listening to DP 4 today, first time in a long while.  this DS is so chill, but is starting to wake up around 16:oo mark here.. then Lesh starts to strut that riff from whatever song that was that they stole those chords from ...its cool
live at the fillmore 1970-02-13 great show u had to be there awesome show
What  a surprise! What a joy as of late to see these previously restricted shows available for listening.  Thanks for the 50th anniversary present!

A Time Traveler... Mighty fine little electric set
and that monster SMOKESTACK!

Acoustic Set- A lot of Bear's Choice. 
pretty sweet Uncle John's Band :)

Electric----Dark Star> OTHER ONE >Lovelight!
That is one good hour and half worth of music.
Goodnight-"Walking in Jerusalem just like John"
2/13/70-So much great music!!!

Forty seven years ago today I've been listening to the second set of this show since I first discovered the boys. This was my proper introduction to the band and of course  this was what sealed the deal with me, in particular the Dark Star -though the rest of the set is just as solid. An amazing display of the bands versatility and skill. My entire way of thinking about music was blown away with that old boot. SO glad I gave it a chance. Would love to hear a note for note recreation of the Dark Star from this show performed or recorded by a symphony just to hear how it sounds. Just like my soul singing. 

But

Primal--> Proper Primal NY hyped Dead. Acoustic set of hippie harmonies. Hint of what would become their Set I intro and Set II nasty stuff. 
The intimate setting would remain for 10 more years till the dance halls gave way to the hockey rinks then the stadiums.
Enjoy with unbridled joy. This date and the next covers it all. 
Rejoice in listening in on a time that can never be repeated. Just to pull this Feb'70 show off a couple of months after Altamont is impressive. 


5/5 all day long.
Proto Beautiful Jam I hear proto elements of the beautiful jam in this Dark  Star— 1 year before it happened.

Top Ten Dark Star > Cryp > OO > Cryp > Lovelight I happen to agree with most of Rolling Stone's 20 essential shows to have. And this late show is one of those essentials per David Fricke. It would have been interesting checking out NJPG's other Dark Star's to have from this era... if he had identified them. Oh well? Mine are 11/11/73 and 9/21/72 as #1 and #2 overall. This one et al is definitely in the top ten, also being in agreement with many of the other reviewers. I never have cared for the deep space of later years since screeching and feedback just isn't my thing. And there is none of it here.

But what I find as amazing as the music is the respect (and probably awe) the audience had for the performance. As another reviewer commented (being there that night) in the quietest moments of Dark Star, you could hear a pin drop in the audience. And for that to happen with a rollicksome, frolicsome, drug-crazed New York City crowd - THAT's saying something!

Dick's Pick's #4 is simply gorgeous as a pristine document. I've copied this version for comparison. But DP4 is beyond compare for sound quality...my having to add a little bass and reverb to soften its brightness. Love the NFA tease before The Other One.  Also loved Bear's Choice from the first day I spun it many many moons ago, mixing this and the 14th's acoustic with Reckoning.

not fade away it's hard to believe that things like this exist.  but, then again, these hippies knew what they were doing (and weren't high enough) that somehow, miraculously, this tape and others like it survived.  who could have thought all of us would be sitting here? Charlie Miller, included. Listening avidly to the pin-drop nuances that separate these shows from one another...certainly, not me.  and  it makes virtually zero sense.  but  I'm happy to realize it before its long-gone.  what others might not have the same luck to find themselves.  I've downloaded the show, and have it saved on my computer.  heck, I even found DP4 in the record store  just the other day! 

this date (and the following day) I hold close to my heart.  it's strange, but  I don't know where I would be without Music.  not just the Dead but so much like them.  Bob Dylan, Radiohead, Joni Mitchell, Miles Davis...where would any of us be without Music,  or Art? I don't care to imagine,  because we have them...anyway,   thanks for the upload. 

* Nick, 12/02/2022

This time period After the more raunchy style of the early dead here they come charging into 1970. Incredibly tight with total perfection. Their sound and style is just so perfect. Weir who usually doesn’t get a lot of credit is playing at his best. This show is a perfect example of this. Pig has so much energy and the band feeds off of this. Phil, well what can you say about Phil? He’s playing lead practically along with Jerry. They had many styles over the years and they changed rapidly after Pig died, never for the better in my opinion although the  early Godchaux years were quite good but this is on another level all together. It’s worth listening to every show from 1970. RIP GD.
